    "recap_headline": "Boston College Athletics",
    "recap_text": "CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. \u2014\nBoston College Baseball (12-8, 3-3 ACC) defeated Sacred Heart (4-13, 3-3 MAAC), 5-4 on Tuesday afternoon.\nDrew Grumbles\nstarted for the Eagles and went two innings, allowing just one run and one hit while striking out two.\nJohn D Mitchell\ncame on in relief and threw three scoreless innings and matched his career high in strikeouts with six.\nSean Hard\npitched the sixth inning and gave up one earned run while striking out three.\nJohn Kwiatkowski\npitched two innings of relief, giving up two earned runs.\nTyler Mudd\nclosed the game out as he induced three fly outs to secure his first save of the season.\nThe Pioneers got on the board in the top of the first when they led off with a double, and the runner advanced on a wild pitch. After Grumbles struck out the next batter, the runner would score on a sacrifice fly to center field.\nBoston College tied the game up in the bottom of the first. The Eagles would load the bases up for\nLuke Gallo\n, who was hit by a pitch to score\nTy Mainolfi\nfrom third.\nThe Eagles took the lead in the bottom of the second when Mainolfi lined a single to right field to score\nColin Larson\nfrom second.\nMainolfi made it 3-1 for the Eagles in the bottom of the fourth with his third hit of the afternoon, which scored Larson from second once again.\nSacred Heart would get one run back in the top of the sixth, when they hit a solo shot to left field to make it 3-2.\nIn the bottom of the seventh, Boston College added two runs. The first came when Gallo singled to center to bring in\nJack Toomey\nfrom third. After a pitch hit\nEsteban Garcia\n, Larson took a walk that would bring in Gallo and make it 5-2 Eagles.\nIn the top of the eighth, the Pioneers got two runs back when they hit a 433-foot home run to left center field.\nThe Eagles went quickly in the bottom of the eighth before Mudd came in and closed out the ninth as he worked around walking his first batter.\nUp Next:\nThe Eagles will return to action tomorrow at 2:00 p.m. when they take on UMass Lowell."
